<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-06-29T00:54:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-06-29T00:54:00-05:00" n="779" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d779">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.24/6–2944: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Saudi Arabia</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moose</hi></persName>)
                                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-29T09:00:00+03:06">June
                                        29, 1944—9 a.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received 1:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>185. Yesterday morning British Chargé d’Affaires and I together
                                called on Acting Foreign Minister. I repeated verbally substance of
                                Department’s 1536 to Cairo, June 20, 6 p.m., and of similar message
                                from Landis (Cairo’s June 22, 8 a.m.) which had already been
                                communicated in writing. British Chargé stated that his Government
                                in replying to King’s message had expressed hope of prompt solution
                                of Saudi supply problem and had added that necessary instructions
                                were already on their way to Cairo.</p>
                            <p>Importance of this communication can only be judged on disclosure of
                                nature of instructions about which British Chargé knows nothing.</p>
                            <p>Sent Department. Repeated to Cairo for Landis.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moose</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>